\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Big Data - Visualization Tool
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Daniel Mínguez Camacho, Yoselin Garcia Salinas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
December 9th, 2018
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Problem characterization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the beggining of the master, we have talked about the european commision
 program 'Horizon 2020' in several courses (Innovation & Entrepreneurship
 or Big Data for example).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the reason why we wanted to take advantage of this assignment in
 order to to dive a little bit in the different projects, organizations
 and topics that are part of it and know how much money it is used in this
 kind of projects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have approach this assignment by concibing our potential users as citizens
 from the european union looking for information regarding H2020.
 We have tried to answer the potential questions that they could have regarding
 the different projects, budget, organizations and researchers that are
 part of this objective 2020.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Regarding the budget:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Which is the total budget dedicated to this projects?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How is the budget divided between countries?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Has the budget evolve during years or has it maintain constant?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Would be possible to start these research projects without european funding?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Regarding organizations
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Which organizations work together in some projects? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Which organizations have more researchers?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Where are these organizations located?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Which are the coordinators of these projects?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Regarding projects:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
How many projects are being develop in each country?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How are the projects distributed along a specific country?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Which are the countries with more projects? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How many projects started in a year in each country? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How many projects started in certain period in each country?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Regarding topics:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Which topics are more recurrent?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Which topics receive more funding?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How topics are related with one another?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
After this first approach to the problem, we tried to look for this information
 in the CORDIS webpage 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "https://cordis.europa.eu/"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in order to know more about the elements present in our dataset.
 We have realized that a worldmap that shows the organizations part of the
 H2020 is available 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "https://cordis.europa.eu/datalab/datalab.php"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and that anyone can look for projects in this 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "link"
target "https://cordis.europa.eu/projects/home_en.html"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have also analyzed the different datasets that we have chosen (explained
 in second point) as detailed in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Input files
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 tab, in order to have a first approach, we decided to include this analysis
 in the visualization as in this design:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename layouts/files.PNG
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After analyzing the information that we have available and compare this
 information with the problems that we want to adress, we have decided to
 do the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Perform a 
\series bold
first approach analysis
\series default
 for each file as detailed in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Input Files
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 tab, here it is possible to find some first approach visualization as:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Organizations:
\series default
 Pie charts representing the contribution per country and the roles of the
 organizations in projects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Projects: 
\series default
A barplot representing the european contribution per year and a scatterplot
 representing the logs of the european contribution to each project versus
 the total cost, that represents that almost any project would have been
 possible without eruopean funding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
General:
\series default
 It is possible to find tables with the details of each file.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Represent the funding that each country receives
\series default
, since little information is available about this topic in the web at a
 first stage.
 In order to do this we have decided to create a treemap representing the
 number of projects and the funding received per country, including more
 details about wich regions/organizations receive this funding.
 This is the first design we did:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename layouts/kpi2.PNG
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The map available in the web represents all organizations across the world,
 but we considered more interesting to know 
\series bold
where are located the organizations that are coordinators
\series default
 of some of the projects, in order to know if entities outside europe can
 coordinate and request projects, in order to do that, we decided to elaborate
 a map locating the different coordinators:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename layouts/MAP Layout.PNG
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the map available in the web it is possible to know
\series bold
 wich organization works with another
\series default
, but in some cases it becomes unfeasible to follow the connections (for
 example if you go to madrid you can see around 300 dots in Puerta del Sol).
 This is the reason why we chose to create a Graph, including also researchers,
 in order to make this analysis easier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename layouts/graph.PNG
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finally, in the web page we have several classifications regarding topics
 (by country, by general topic), but unless you know what you are looking
 for, it is difficult to have a 
\series bold
global overview of the different topics
\series default
, this is why we decided to make a TF-IDF scatterplot, showing the 10 more
 relevant words for each topic visually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename layouts/algorithm.PNG
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Dataset choosen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found the following files in the European Data Portal
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
